The smallest acceptable decision is: add a dedicated bulk handler that splits `request validation` from `per-account execution`, and never uses exception catching as normal item control flow.

Anything smaller than that collapses the trust boundary and makes the result contract unprovable.

A minimal implementation slice I would accept is:

```ts
// Trust boundary types
interface BulkActivateRequest {
  accountIds: string[];
}

type ItemStatus =
  | 'activated'
  | 'already-active'
  | 'not-found'
  | 'unauthorized';

interface ItemResult {
  accountId: string;
  status: ItemStatus;
}

interface BulkActivateResponse {
  results: ItemResult[];
  summary: {
    activated: number;
    alreadyActive: number;
    notFound: number;
    unauthorized: number;
    total: number;
  };
}

function validateBulkActivateRequest(body: unknown): BulkActivateRequest {
  if (typeof body !== 'object' || body === null || Array.isArray(body)) {
    throw badRequest('body must be an object');
  }

  const accountIds = (body as Record<string, unknown>).accountIds;
  if (!Array.isArray(accountIds)) {
    throw badRequest('accountIds must be an array');
  }
  if (accountIds.length < 1 || accountIds.length > 100) {
    throw badRequest('accountIds must contain 1 to 100 items');
  }

  const seen = new Set<string>();
  for (const id of accountIds) {
    if (!isValidAccountId(id)) {
      throw badRequest('every accountId must be valid');
    }
    if (seen.has(id)) {
      throw badRequest('accountIds must be distinct');
    }
    seen.add(id);
  }

  return { accountIds };
}

async function bulkActivate(body: unknown, actor: Actor): Promise<BulkActivateResponse> {
  const { accountIds } = validateBulkActivateRequest(body);

  const results: ItemResult[] = [];

  for (const accountId of accountIds) {
    if (!(await authz.canActivate(actor, accountId))) {
      results.push({ accountId, status: 'unauthorized' });
      continue;
    }

    const outcome = await accounts.activate(accountId);
    results.push({ accountId, status: mapOutcome(outcome) });
  }

  return summarize(results);
}

function mapOutcome(outcome: ActivateOutcome): ItemStatus {
  switch (outcome) {
    case 'activated':
    case 'already-active':
    case 'not-found':
      return outcome;
  }
}

function summarize(results: ItemResult[]): BulkActivateResponse {
  const summary = {
    activated: 0,
    alreadyActive: 0,
    notFound: 0,
    unauthorized: 0,
    total: results.length,
  };

  for (const r of results) {
    if (r.status === 'activated') summary.activated++;
    else if (r.status === 'already-active') summary.alreadyActive++;
    else if (r.status === 'not-found') summary.notFound++;
    else summary.unauthorized++;
  }

  return { results, summary };
}
```

Why this is the minimum:
- Validation happens once, before any side effects. That is required by the spec.
- Authorization is per account, not global and not exception-driven.
- Every valid ID gets an item result.
- Summary counts are mechanically derived from item results, so they cannot drift.
- Typed collaborator outcomes are preserved instead of being flattened into catch-all error handling.

The manager’s happy-path shortcut is not acceptable because it breaks at least three required properties:
- A loop over untrusted `body.accounts` without prior full validation can partially mutate before discovering an invalid later item.
- Catching every error erases the specified distinction between `already-active`, `not-found`, and `unauthorized`.
- Returning only “number attempted” discards the required per-ID result contract and makes summary correctness uncheckable.

Focused tests I would require for this slice:
- Reject non-object body.
- Reject missing or non-array `accountIds`.
- Reject empty array.
- Reject more than 100 IDs.
- Reject duplicate IDs.
- Reject any invalid ID and verify no authz, persistence, or audit calls occurred.
- For mixed valid IDs, return one result per input in input order.
- `unauthorized` result is emitted when authz fails and persistence is not called for that ID.
- Persistence outcomes `activated`, `already-active`, and `not-found` map exactly to response statuses.
- Summary counts equal the counted item results, including `total`.

If the team wants the absolute smallest reusable shape, make `validateBulkActivateRequest`, `mapOutcome`, and `summarize` pure functions, then keep the handler body as the only async orchestration layer. That is the narrowest design that still satisfies the specification defensibly.
